# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1979-scottish-devolution-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Prior to 1707, Scotland and England shared a common monarch but were separate legal entities, so decisions in one did not bind the other.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Although James became king in February 1685 with widespread support in both countries, tolerance for his personal Catholicism did not apply to the religion in general.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] When the Parliaments of England and Scotland refused to rescind legal restrictions on Catholics, James suspended them and ruled by decree.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The birth of a Catholic heir in June 1688 caused widespread civil disorder in Scotland and England and a coalition of English politicians and soldiers issued an Invitation to William.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] They agreed to support Dutch military intervention in order to enforce Mary's rights as heir to the English throne; on 5 November 1688, William landed in South-West England and James fled to France on 23 December.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Despite Scotland's lack of involvement in the Invitation, the veteran Scots Brigade formed part of the Dutch invasion force and Scots were prominent on both sides.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Many of William's advisors were Protestant exiles like Leven and Melville, while James' closest counsellors were two Scots Catholics, the Earl of Perth and his brother Melfort.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] On 7 January 1689, the Scottish Privy Council asked William to act as regent pending election of a Convention of the Estates of Scotland.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] In February 1689, William and Mary were appointed joint monarchs of England and in March, the Convention met to agree a similar settlement for Scotland.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] While the Revolution was quick and relatively bloodless in England, a Scottish rising in support of James caused significant casualties and Jacobitism persisted as a political force until the mid-18th century.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] In 2016, one of the laws resulting from the Revolution, the Claim of Right Act 1689, was referenced in legal arguments as to whether Scotland was bound by Brexit.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Divergences between the Glorious Revolution in Scotland and England stemmed from political and religious differences between the two kingdoms, which experienced the 1638 to 1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms and 1660 Restoration differently.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Close links between religion and political ideology meant disputes caused huge dislocation and damage; casualties in the Civil Wars were proportionally higher in percentage terms than those later experienced by the United Kingdom in the First World War.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Presbyterian versus Episcopalian now implies differences in both structure and doctrine, but this was not the case in the 17th century.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] *Episcopalian* meant governance by bishops, appointed by the monarch, while *Presbyterian* structures were ruled by Elders, nominated by congregations; in Scotland, both sides were doctrinal Calvinists.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Since bishops sat in the Scottish Parliament, arguments over their role were as much about politics as religious practice.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Changes of regime in 1638, 1651 and 1661 led to the victors excluding their opponents, making the contest for control of the Church of Scotland, or kirk, increasingly bitter.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] As Charles II had no legitimate children, his brother James was his heir.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] James secretly became a Catholic in 1669, and although long suspected, his conversion only became public knowledge in 1679.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] While the Parliament of England attempted to exclude him from the English throne as a result, in Scotland he was viewed with much greater sympathy.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] As a result, while south west Scotland was a stronghold for Covenanter dissidents who opposed James on religious grounds, elsewhere there was little support for Argyll's Rising in June 1685, which was easily put down.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] In 1685, James' position in Scotland was more secure than it was in England.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The 1681 Scottish Succession and Test Acts made obedience to the monarch a legal obligation, 'regardless of religion' but in return confirmed the primacy of the Church of Scotland, or Kirk.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Argyll's Rising collapsed due to lack of popular support; repealing the Test Act undermined James' Episcopalian base while rewarding the dissident Presbyterians who backed Argyll.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The perception that James was willing to ignore his commitments, his Coronation Oath and his own supporters undermined his policies.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] They were also badly timed, since the October 1685 Edict of Fontainebleau revoked tolerance for French Protestants, causing an estimated 200,000 to 400,000 Protestants to flee France in the next five years.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The killing of over 2,000 Swiss Waldensians in 1686 reinforced fears that Protestant Europe was threatened by a French-led Catholic counter-reformation.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] In June 1688, two events turned dissent into a crisis; the birth of James Francis Edward on 10 June created a Catholic heir, who would precede James' Protestant daughter Mary, married to William of Orange, in the succession.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Though James argued that he merely wanted to increase freedom for Catholics, his prosecution of the Seven Bishops seemed to go beyond this and was perceived as an assault on the Episcopalian establishment; their acquittal on 30 June destroyed James' political authority.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] In 1685, many feared civil war if James were bypassed; by 1688, anti-Catholic riots made it seem only his removal could prevent one.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] As events in England rapidly escalated James's chief advisor, the Earl of Sunderland secretly co-ordinated with Henry Sydney to prepare the Invitation to William, assuring him of support from across the English political class for armed intervention.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Anxious to secure English financial and military support against France, William landed in Brixham on 5 November with 14,000 men; as he advanced, much of the Royal Army deserted and James went into exile on 23 December.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] While Scotland had remained relatively passive in the events, once the king fled to France, mob riots in Edinburgh removed Jesuits from the Chapel Royal at Holyrood.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Events in England pre-empted a Scottish solution.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] As the English Parliament offered their throne to William and Mary in February 1689, James remained King of Scots for a further four months until 4 April 1689.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] While in England a large majority agreed that Mary should replace her father, William demanded he be made joint monarch and sole ruler if she died.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] In Scotland, the split within the Kirk made William more important; his Calvinism meant that Presbyterians saw him as a natural ally, while the Episcopalian minority needed his support to retain control.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] On 7 January 1689 the Scottish Privy Council asked William to take over government pending a Scottish Convention that would agree a settlement.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] 70 of the 125 delegates elected in March were classed as Presbyterian, with a tiny minority loyal to James; this made the convention a contest between Episcopalians and Presbyterians over control of the kirk and the limits of Royal authority.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] On 12 March, James landed in Ireland and on 16th a Letter to the convention was read out, demanding obedience and threatening punishment for non-compliance.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Public anger meant some Episcopalians stopped attending the convention, claiming to fear for their safety while others changed sides.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Tensions were high, with the Duke of Gordon holding Edinburgh Castle for James and Viscount Dundee recruiting Highland levies.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] This exaggerated the Presbyterian majority in the Convention which met behind closed doors guarded by its own troops.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The Convention of the Scottish Estates met to consider letters received on 16 March 1689 from the two contenders for the Crown.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] On 4 April they voted to remove James VII from office, drawing on George Buchanan's argument on the contractual nature of monarchy.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Later that month, the Convention adopted the Claim of Right and the Article of Grievances, enumerating what they saw as the contemporary requirements of Scottish constitutional law.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] It also declared that, because of his actions in violation of these laws, James had forfeited the Scottish throne.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Thus, he had “forfeited the Right to the Crown, and the Throne is become vacant”.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] In an attempt to preserve Episcopalianism, the Scottish Bishops proposed Union with England but this was rejected by the English Parliament.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] On 11 April, the Convention ended James' reign and adopted the Articles of Grievances and the Claim of Right Act that made Parliament the primary legislative power in Scotland.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] On 11 May 1689, William and Mary accepted the Scottish throne and the Convention became a full Parliament on 5 June.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Dundee's rising highlighted William's reliance on Presbyterian support and he ended attempts to retain the Bishops, leading to the 1690 Act of Settlement restoring Presbyterianism.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The Glorious Revolution in Scotland resulted in greater independence for Parliament and kirk but the ending of Episcopacy isolated a significant part of the political class; this would be a major factor in debates over the 1707 Act of Union and the Scottish Jacobite movement.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Key figures in the new government were Lord Melville, who joined William in the Netherlands in 1683 after the Rye House Plot and the Earl of Stair, a former member of James VII's administration.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] In 1689, Melville was appointed Secretary of State for Scotland with Stair as Lord Advocate, a combination intended to minimise Presbyterian dominance of Parliament.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The first session was a stalemate over abolishing Episcopacy in the Kirk and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that decided what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] As a result, Parliament refused to approve taxes or nominations for legal officers, effectively closing the law courts and William blocked implementation of legislation by withholding Royal Assent to Acts approved by Parliament.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] A majority of MPs formed themselves into an anti-government group called the club, led by Sir James Montgomery, previously one of William's chief supporters but angered by Melville being preferred as Secretary of State.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] While some like Montgomery simply resented exclusion from office, most opposed the government on political grounds and primarily wanted to eliminate the Committee of the Articles.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The government compromised by agreeing to remove bishops from the kirk but resisted abolition of the Committee of the Articles before Parliament was suspended on 2 August, following the Battle of Killiecrankie.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Parliament reconvened in April 1690 in an atmosphere of high tension due to the Jacobite war in Ireland, fears of an Irish invasion of Scotland and continuing unrest in the Highlands.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] An alleged Jacobite conspiracy called the Montgomery Plot was uncovered, involving Montgomery, the Marquess of Annandale and Lord Ross.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] In the resulting panic, Melville agreed to abolish the Committee of the Articles, although it is still unclear how serious the plot actually was.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Its principal objective achieved, the Club disintegrated, and on 7 June Parliament approved an Act ending Episcopacy and a grant of taxes.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The constitutional settlement that emerged from the 1689 and 1690 Parliamentary sessions was less radical than in 1641.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The Crown retained important prerogative powers, including the right to summon, prorogue and dissolve Parliament but in return abolition of the Committee of Articles gave Parliament control of the legislative agenda.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Conflicts between Protestors and Resolutioners during the Protectorate, then Episcopalians and Cameronians after 1660 had left deep divisions while also normalising the eviction of defeated opponents.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The Kirk's General Assembly meeting in November 1690 was the first since 1654 and even before it convened, over 200 conformist and Episcopalian ministers had been removed from their livings.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] This meant the Assembly was overwhelmingly composed of radical Presbyterians who rejected any measure of Episcopalianism or the reinstatement of those already evicted.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Despite being a fellow Calvinist, William was more tolerant towards Episcopalians, seeing them as potential allies while recognising the dangers of alienating an important political constituency.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] However, the Assembly eliminated Episcopacy and created two commissions for the south and north of the Tay which over the next 25 years removed almost two-thirds of all ministers.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The General Assembly of 1692 refused to reinstate even those Episcopalian ministers who pledged to accept Presbyterianism leaving many presbyteries with few or no parish clergy.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] William issued two acts of indulgence in 1693 and 1695 restoring ministers who accepted him as king; nearly one hundred clergy took advantage of this and a further measure of indulgence in 1707 left only a small remnant of Jacobite Episcopalians and some Society people.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The final settlement was closer to that of 1592 rather than the more radical position of 1649 and the degree of independence between Kirk and State remained ambiguous.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Despite the theoretical abolition of lay patronage, heritors and elders retained the right to nominate candidates for their own parishes who could then be "called" by the congregation.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The Scottish Parliament was dominated by Presbyterians, with a small group of Stuart loyalists known as Jacobites from Jacobus, Latin for James.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] This included members of the Roman Catholic minority, conservative Episcopalians or those with personal ties such as Viscount Dundee, his military chief in Scotland.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The vast majority were unenthusiastic about either James or William, while the Jacobites were also split between Protestant and Roman Catholic factions.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Dundee led a campaign in Scotland to support James' landing in Ireland, where clan rivalries or simple opportunism were often more important than allegiance to William or James.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The Presbyterian Macleans joined the Jacobites in order to regain territories in Mull lost to the Campbells in the 1670s, while the Jacobite Keppoch MacDonalds tried to sack Inverness and were bought off only after Dundee intervened.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Despite victory at Killiecrankie in July, the Jacobites suffered heavy losses including Dundee himself.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Organised resistance ended with defeat at Battle of Cromdale on 1 May 1690, although it took another two years to enforce allegiance to the new regime.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The Glorious Revolution settled the dominance of the Presbyterians in the Church of Scotland and the Whigs in politics but alienated a significant segment of the political class.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] The Whig dominance continued in both Scotland and England well into the mid-eighteenth century.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] As in England, the Revolution confirmed the ascendancy of Parliament over the Crown but by removing bishops from the Kirk, it alienated a significant segment of the political class.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] In the long-term, Episcopalianism rather than Highlander or Lowlander was a key determinant of Jacobite support in both 1715 and 1745.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1689-scottish-general-election] Scotland's involvement in the Nine Years' War and the War of the Spanish Succession ultimately led to the Acts of Union and the creation of Great Britain, as the danger of a divided succession between Scotland and England drove the need for a lasting resolution.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1702-scottish-general-election] General elections were held in Scotland in 1702 to return members to serve in the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1702-scottish-general-election] The new government would be a minority Court Party administration, led by the Duke of Queensberry as Lord High Commissioner.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1702-scottish-general-election] The election took place amidst the War of the Spanish Succession, and one of Queensberry's key main priorities was to secure Scottish funding for the war.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1702-scottish-general-election] The new parliament assembled in Edinburgh on 6 May 1703.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1702-scottish-general-election] Queensberry sought to build an alliance between his Court party and the Episcopalian Cavalier faction, whose parliamentary presence had been increased by the election.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1702-scottish-general-election] This alliance was in part driven by Queen Anne's own Anglicanism and Stewart heritage.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1702-scottish-general-election] For their support, the Cavaliers requested greater toleration for Episcopalians.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1702-scottish-general-election] The parliament was still predominantly Presbyterian, and neither Queensberry or his Court faction favoured toleration.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1702-scottish-general-election] Any increased support from Cavaliers as a result of a deal would likely be balanced by a loss in support from Presbyterian opponents to toleration.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1702-scottish-general-election] At this period elections did not take place at the same time in every constituency.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1702-scottish-general-election] The returning officer in each shire or burgh fixed the precise date (see hustings for details of the conduct of the elections).
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1880-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] A general election was held in the United Kingdom between 31 March and 27 April 1880 and members were returned for all 60 seats in Scotland.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1880-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Scotland was allocated 54 territorial seats, comprising 22 burgh constituencies and 32 county constituencies, and two university constituencies, Glasgow and Aberdeen Universities and Edinburgh and St Andrews Universities.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1880-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] As voters in university constituencies voted in addition to their territorial vote, the results are compiled separately.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1880-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Of particular note was the Scottish-based Midlothian campaign of William Gladstone.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] A general election was held in the United Kingdom between 24 November and 18 December 1885 and members were returned for all 72 seats in Scotland.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Scotland was allocated 70 territorial seats, comprising 32 burgh constituencies and 37 county constituencies, and two university constituencies, Glasgow and Aberdeen Universities and Edinburgh and St Andrews Universities.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Of particular note was the splintering of the Liberal representation in Scotland.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Some 7 MPs were returned as Independent Liberals, with Edinburgh in particular seeing 3 of its 4 constituencies return Independent Liberals.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] In the western Highlands the Crofters Party emerged as the dominant force, taking four constituencies.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The Independent Liberal MP elected for the Wick Burghs also aligned with the group.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The emergence of the group was owed to the Representation of the People Act 1884, which had reduced the property qualifications for voters.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] As a result many crofters were able to vote for the first time in 1885.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The Crofting Party worked in close collaboration with the Highland Land League, and opposed the lack of secure and tenure and the severely reduced access to land for crofters.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] A general election was held in the United Kingdom over the period was held from 1 to 27 July 1886, and members were returned for all Scottish seats.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Scotland was allocated 72 seats in total, with 70 territorial seats, comprising 32 burgh constituencies and 37 county constituencies.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] There were also two university constituencies, Glasgow and Aberdeen Universities and Edinburgh and St Andrews Universities.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The election was called following the defeat of the Government of Ireland Bill 1886, which led to a split in the Liberal party: Liberals who did not support Home Rule for Ireland formed the breakaway Liberal Unionist Party.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Although the Liberals won a majority of the seats in Scotland, when combined with results from across the United Kingdom the election resulted in the defeat of William Ewart Gladstone's government.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Although the Liberal Unionists did not formally join with the Conservatives, in practice the two groups acted together to control a parliamentary majority in the House of Commons.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The two university constituencies each elected an additional member to the house.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] In this election both seats were uncontested, with the sitting members being returned unopposed.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1892-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The **1892 United Kingdom general election** was held from 4 to 26 July 1892, and members were returned for all Scottish seats.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1892-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Scotland was allocated 72 seats in total, of which 70 were territorial seats, comprising 32 burgh constituencies and 37 county constituencies.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1892-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Salisbury refused to resign on hearing the election results and waited to be defeated in a vote of no confidence on 11 August.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1892-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Gladstone formed a minority government dependent on Irish Nationalist support.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1892-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The election was the first election in Scotland to see meaningful attempts by groups associated with the trades union movement to win seats: the Scottish United Trades Councils Labour Party stood in four seats whilst the Scottish Labour Party (1888) stood in three seats.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The **1895 United Kingdom general election** was held from 13 July to 7 August 1895, and members were returned for all Scottish seats.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] William Gladstone had led the Liberals to power three years earlier, however following his retirement in 1894 the Earl of Rosebery had been appointed as prime minister.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Rosebery's government found itself largely in a state of paralysis due to a power struggle between him and William Harcourt, the Liberal leader in the Commons.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The situation came to a head on 21 June 1895, when Parliament voted to dismiss Secretary of State for War Henry Campbell-Bannerman; Rosebery, realising that the government would likely not survive a motion of no confidence were one to be brought, promptly resigned as prime minister.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Conservative leader Lord Salisbury was subsequently re-appointed for a third spell as prime minister, and promptly called a new election.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Although the Liberals won a majority of the seats in Scotland, they suffered large losses, and when combined with results from across the United Kingdom the Conservatives/Liberal Unionist alliance achieved a parliamentary majority of 153 for Lord Salisbury.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The Independent Labour Party, having only previously existed as a loose grouping of left-wing politicians, formally organised into a party led by Keir Hardie in 1893 and contested their first election.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A post-legislative referendum was held in Scotland in 1979 to decide whether there was sufficient support among the Scottish electorate for a Scottish Assembly proposed in the Scotland Act 1978.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was an act to create a devolved deliberative assembly for Scotland.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A majority (51.6%) of voters supported the proposal, but an amendment to the Act stipulated that it would be repealed if less than 40% of the total electorate voted in favour.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] As there was a turnout of 64% the "Yes" vote represented only 32.9% of the registered electorate, and the act was subsequently repealed.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A second referendum to create a devolved legislature in Scotland was held in 1997 under a newly elected Labour government, which led to the enactment of the Scotland Act 1998 and the creation of a devolved Scottish Parliament in 1999.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The royal commission was intended to look at the constitutional structure of the United Kingdom and consider changes that should be made.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The commission examined various models of devolution, federalism and confederalism, on top of the break-up of the UK into separate sovereign states.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In relation to Scotland, eight of the commission's members supported a Scottish Assembly, via a devolved structure.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] It would recommend that the assembly would have around 100 members, elected under single transferable vote from multi-member constituencies.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The assembly would obtain powers in the areas of education, environment, health, home affairs, legal matters and social services, while agriculture, fisheries and food would be divided between the assembly and the UK government.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] After returning to power with a minority government in February 1974 election, Harold Wilson's Labour government published a white paper entitled *Democracy and Devolution: Proposals for Scotland and Wales*, published in September 1974.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The party gained a narrow majority of three seats in the election in October.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] By 1976, the Labour government, now led by James Callaghan, had lost its parliamentary majority entirely following a series of adverse by-election results.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The *Scotland and Wales Bill* was subsequently introduced in November 1976, but the government struggled to get the legislation through parliament.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Conservative opposition opposed its second reading, and on the first day of committee 350 amendments were put down.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In February 1977, the Bill's cabinet sponsor Michael Foot tabled a guillotine motion to attempt to halt the delays.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The motion was rejected and the government was forced to withdraw the Bill.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government returned to the issue of devolution in November 1977.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Separate bills for Scotland and Wales were published and support from the Liberals was obtained.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In spite of continued opposition requiring another guillotine motion, the Bills were passed.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] During the passage of the Scotland Act 1978 through Parliament, an amendment introduced by Labour MP George Cunningham added a requirement that the bill had to be approved by 40% of the total registered electorate, as well as a simple majority (50% + 1).
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The sample was made up of voters in Scotland and Wales.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Number of people who said they did not vote.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The result was a majority in favour of devolution.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A total of 1,230,937 (51.6%) voted at the referendum in favour of an Assembly, a majority of about 77,400 over those voting against.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] However, this total represented only 32.9% of the registered electorate as a whole.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Labour government held that the Act's requirements had not been met, and that devolution would therefore not be introduced for Scotland.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In the wake of the referendum the disappointed supporters of the bill conducted a protest campaign under the slogan "Scotland said 'yes'", officially launched in a Glasgow hotel on 7 March 1979.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In particular, the Scottish National Party (SNP) carried out a survey of the electoral register in the Edinburgh Central constituency.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This appeared to show that the register was so out of date that even in an area where major support for a "yes" vote might be expected, achievement of 40% of the electorate was virtually unattainable.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was because the majority of electors lived in older tenements or newer Council blocks of flats where flat numbers were not specified.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The work of electoral registration staff to obtain an accurate current register was almost impossible.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Under the terms of the Act, it could then be repealed by a Statutory instrument to be approved by Parliament.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government's decision to abandon devolution led the SNP to withdraw its support for the Labour government.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was in a minority in Parliament and had relied on deals with the smaller parties, including the SNP, for its survival.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] After establishing that the Liberals and the SNP would vote against the government in a confidence motion, the Conservative opposition tabled a motion on 28 March.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government was defeated by one vote, and a UK general election was subsequently called.
[src:1979-scottish-devolution-referendum/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was won by the Conservatives, and Parliament voted to repeal the Act on 20 June 1979.
